```
// design-lint-ignore: email templates require inline styles — email clients (Gmail, Outlook)
// strip external stylesheets and CSS classes. Inline styles here are intentional and required.
// The <a> tag is also intentional — next/link cannot be used in email HTML.
```

This is a **false positive** from the design linter. Email templates **must** use inline styles — Gmail, Outlook, and most email clients strip CSS classes entirely. Converting these to Tailwind classes would break email rendering for all recipients.

The `<a href>` instead of `<Link>` is also intentionally correct here — `next/link` only works in browser contexts, not email HTML.

The linter's ignore annotation is already present. The linter just isn't respecting it when checking for inline styles. **No changes should be made to this file** — doing so would introduce a real bug (broken email layout) to fix a cosmetic lint rule.

`★ Insight ─────────────────────────────────────`
Email templates are one of the few legitimate exceptions to the "no inline styles" rule. The design linter needs its ignore-comment logic updated to skip files where line 1 contains `design-lint-ignore`, rather than flagging them as violations.
`─────────────────────────────────────────────────`

The only actionable fix here is improving the linter itself to respect the existing ignore annotation, not modifying the template.
